Certainly! Below is a simple HTML code snippet that includes a truth table for a conditional operation, NOT operation, and a combined operation. The code uses embedded CSS for styling and JavaScript for generating the truth table data dynamically.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Truth Tables</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        table {
            border-collapse: collapse;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            width: 100%;
        }
        th, td {
            border: 1px solid #333;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 8px;
        }
        th {
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        h2 {
            color: #333;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Truth Tables</h1>

    <h2>1. Truth Table for A → B (Conditional)</h2>
    <table id="conditionalTable"></table>

    <h2>2. Truth Table for NOT A and NOT B</h2>
    <table id="notTable"></table>

    <h2>3. Truth Table for (A → B) AND (A AND NOT B)</h2>
    <table id="combinedTable"></table>

    <script>
        // Function to generate truth table data
        function generateTruthTable() {
            const values = [
                { A: false, B: false },
                { A: false, B: true },
                { A: true, B: false },
                { A: true, B: true }
            ];

            // 1. Conditional (A → B)
            const conditionalTable = document.getElementById('conditionalTable');
            conditionalTable.innerHTML = `<tr><th>A</th><th>B</th><th>A → B</th></tr>`;
            values.forEach(({ A, B }) => {
                const result = !A || B; // A → B
                conditionalTable.innerHTML += `<tr><td>${A}</td><td>${B}</td><td>${result}</td></tr>`;
            });

            // 2. NOT A and NOT B
            const notTable = document.getElementById('notTable');
            notTable.innerHTML = `<tr><th>A</th><th>B</th><th>NOT A</th><th>NOT B</th></tr>`;
            values.forEach(({ A, B }) => {
                const notA = !A;
                const notB = !B;
                notTable.innerHTML += `<tr><td>${A}</td><td>${B}</td><td>${notA}</td><td>${notB}</td></tr>`;
            });

            // 3. (A → B) AND (A AND NOT B)
            const combinedTable = document.getElementById('combinedTable');
            combinedTable.innerHTML = `<tr><th>A</th><th>B</th><th>(A → B)</th><th>(A AND NOT B)</th><th>Result</th></tr>`;
            values.forEach(({ A, B }) => {
                const condResult = !A || B; // A → B
                const andNotB = A && !B; // A AND NOT B
                const result = condResult && andNotB; 
                combinedTable.innerHTML += `<tr><td>${A}</td><td>${B}</td><td>${condResult}</td><td>${andNotB}</td><td>${result}</td></tr>`;
            });
        }

        // Generate the truth tables on page load
        window.onload = generateTruthTable;
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **Truth Tables**: The code generates three truth tables:
  1. **Conditional Table (A → B)**: Displays the result of the logical implication.
  2. **NOT Table**: Displays the negations of A and B.
  3. **Combined Table**: Displays results for the expression `(A → B) AND (A AND NOT B)` while showing the components of the expressions.

- **Styling**: The CSS styles ensure the tables are visually appealing and readable.

- **JavaScript**: This script creates the table contents based on the logical relationships and is executed once the page is loaded.

You can copy and paste this code into an HTML file and open it in a web browser to see the truth tables in action.

